<HL> Wall Street Journal Rates
For Ads to Rise in January</HL>
<DD> 11/20/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> DJ
PUBLISHING (PUB) </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dow Jones &amp; Co. announced increases in Wall Street Journal advertising rates for 1988. 

   The new rates, which reflect a 6% increase for national advertising and a 7% increase in regional-edition advertising, will take effect Jan. 4. 

   The Journal will continue to offer its New Business Incentive Plan, which was introduced in 1987, as well as volume and frequency discounts. 
New regional advertising breakouts for New England, the Chicago/Milwaukee area, and the Washington/Baltimore area will be introduced next year. 

   Advertising rates for The Wall Street Journal/Europe, published in Brussels and printed in the Netherlands and Switzerland, will increase 9%. 
The paper is distributed throughout Europe and the Middle East. 
Advertising rates for The Asian Wall Street Journal, published in Hong Kong and also printed in Singapore and Tokyo, will increase 8.5%. 
The paper is distributed throughout Asia. 

   Rates for The Asian Wall Street Journal Weekly, published in New York for North American readers with Asian interests, won't change. 

   Dow Jones also publishes Barron's magazine, domestic and overseas newswires, computerized information retrieval services, and radio and television news reports. 
It also owns 56% of Telerate Inc., a supplier of computerized financial information. 
The Ottaway Newspapers Inc. subsidiary publishes daily community newspapers, while the Richard D. Irwin Inc. subsidiary publishes college textbooks and books for business executives. 

</TEXT>
